{
  "texts": [
    "In the realm of ABSA, discriminative approaches are often used to predict specific task outcomes by designing task-specific classification networks that use class indexes as labels for training.",
    "However, this approach disregards the semantic richness present in labels, and the need for multiple classification models for different ABSA tasks makes it challenging to generalize the model.",
    "To overcome these challenges, Zhang et al. (2021d) proposed a novel approach called Generative-based SA (GAS) that utilizes a unified generative approach to handle various ABSA tasks.",
    "By encoding natural language labels into the target output, the model leverages rich semantic information in labels and can adapt seamlessly to multiple tasks without requiring additional model design.",
    "To train the T5 model, Zhang et al. (2021d) designed a flat sequence including two paradigms, annotation-style (GAS-A) and extraction-style (GAS-E) in Table 10, that frame each ABSA task as a text generation problem."
  ]
}